Node: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal03/short_story_11
typeOf: schema:Article
additionalType: "ShortStory"
name: "Twenty-one million children missed out on lifesaving vaccines in 2022  "
text: "Between 2000 and 2019, the proportion of children receiving three doses of the diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis (DTP3) vaccine rose from 72 to 86 per cent, then dipped to 81 per cent in 2021 before rebounding to 84 per cent in 2022. In 2022, 20.5 million children missed at least one routine vaccine and 14.3 million received no vaccines at all. Coverage of two doses of the measles vaccine and three doses of the pneumococcal conjugate vaccine increased in 2022, reaching 74 per cent and 60 per cent, respectively, following stagnation in 2020‒2021. Global coverage of the human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine, critical for women’s and girls’ health, stood at only 15 per cent in 2022, despite 130 countries introducing it in their national immunization services by the end of the year. \n"
creditText: "United Nations. The Sustainable Development Goals Report 2024."
