Node: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal04/short_story_03
typeOf: schema:Article
additionalType: "ShortStory"
name: "An urgent need for enhanced climate change and sustainability education and teacher training "
text: "Although 90 per cent of countries report that they mainstream sustainable development and global citizenship subjects in national education systems, evidence suggests scattered uptake. A 2023 study of more than 530 ninth grade science and social science curricula found that 69 per cent did not mention climate change and 66 per cent omitted sustainability. Despite claims by some teachers that these topics were covered, 50 per cent admitted to not teaching them. Three quarters of countries expressed intentions to revise their curricula within the next three years to prioritize climate change and sustainability. Simply revising curricula may not be sufficient, however, if teachers lack the confidence or willingness to teach these subjects. Comprehensive support from schools, training institutions, communities and governments is essential to encourage educators to effectively transmit sustainability principles to future generations."
creditText: "United Nations. The Sustainable Development Goals Report 2024."
