Node: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal06/short_story_01
typeOf: schema:Article
additionalType: "ShortStory"
name: "More people have safe drinking water and sanitation but billions still go without "
text: "Between 2015 and 2022, the proportion of the population using safely managed drinking water increased from 69 to 73 per cent. Shares with safely managed sanitation rose from 49 to 57 per cent and with basic hygiene services from 67 to 75 per cent. In 2022, however, 2.2 billion people still lacked safely managed drinking water, 3.5 billion went without safely managed sanitation (including 419 million who practised open defecation) and 2 billion still had inadequate basic hygiene services (including 653 million with no facilities at all). Additionally, 1.8 billion people had no on-premises drinking water, with women primarily responsible for water collection in two out of three households. Achieving universal coverage by 2030 will require a sixfold increase in current rates of progress for safely managed drinking water, a fivefold increase for safely managed sanitation and a threefold increase for basic hygiene services."
creditText: "United Nations. The Sustainable Development Goals Report 2024."
