Node: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal10/short_story_02
typeOf: schema:Article
additionalType: "ShortStory"
name: "Labour’s share of GDP returns to a long-term decline as capital returns increase"
text: "Bucking a downward trend going back to the 1970s, the global labour income share of GDP rose sharply during the pandemic from 52.9 per cent in 2019 to 53.8 per cent in 2020. This increase should not be misinterpreted as a net gain for workers. During this period, global labour income decreased by 1.5 per cent in 2020, while global output fell even more, by 3 per cent.  In 2021, the labour income share of GDP resumed its long-run decline. \n\nThe labour income share of GDP dropped from 54.1 per cent in 2004 to 52.7 per cent in 2021, representing a loss of $568 (purchasing power parity) per worker. This negative trend implies that rising labour productivity has not fully translated into higher labour compensation. Earnings from work are particularly important for less well-off and vulnerable people. At the same time, returns to capital have been rising, which can increase inequality as capital income is concentrated among the affluent. "
image: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal10/figure02
