Node: dcid:undata/article/sdg_report_2024/goal10/short_story_04
typeOf: schema:Article
additionalType: "ShortStory"
name: "Developing countries remain underrepresented in international economic decision-making"
text: "Developing countries make up 74 per cent of United Nations General Assembly Members but have limited voice and participation in international economic decision-making, norm-setting and governance. At the World Bank’s main lending arm, developing countries hold only 39 per cent of voting rights, far short of their 75 per cent share of the bank’s membership. At the International Finance Corporation, the World Bank’s private sector lending arm, developing countries have just over 32 per cent of voting rights. \n\nThe International Monetary Fund completed two general reviews of quotas in 2019 and 2023 without any changes to their distribution (which helps to determine voting rights), leaving developing countries with only 37 per cent of voting rights. Other international financial institutions, such as regional development banks, have not undertaken any voting rights reforms since 2015 or announced plans to do so. The Fourth International Conference on Financing for Development in 2025 presents an opportunity to address these shortcomings and strengthen the legitimacy of global governance arrangements. "
creditText: "United Nations. The Sustainable Development Goals Report 2024."
